{"title_page": "Verizon Wireless", "text_new": "{{short description|US telecommunications company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| trade_name = Verizon Wireless\n| logo = Verizon 2015 logo -vector.svg\n| logo_caption = Verizon's current logo as of September 1, 2015\n| alt = The text \"verizon\" with a red check mark to the right of it\n| type = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| industry = [[Telecommunication]]s\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2000|04|04}} in [[Bedminster, New Jersey|Bedminster]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| founder = [[Vodafone]]<br>[[Bell Atlantic]]\n| location_city = [[Basking Ridge, New Jersey]]\n| locations = 2,330 owned retail stores\n| area_served = United States\n| key_people = [[Hans Vestberg]]<br><small>(CEO, Verizon Communications)</small><br>[[Ronan Dunne]]<br><small> (CEO, Verizon Consumer)</small>\n| services = [[Mobile telephony]]<br>[[Wireless broadband]]\n| parent = \n| owner = [[Verizon Communications]]\n| footnotes = <ref name=\"ver_corp_hist\">{{cite web|url=http://investor.verizon.com/profile/history/|title=The History of Verizon Communications|work=Verizon Wireless|accessdate=May 7, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"VerizonWireless.com\">{{cite web|url=http://aboutus.verizonwireless.com/leadership/executive/index.html |title=Executive Leadership |publisher=Aboutus.verizonwireless.com |accessdate=May 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stores.org/2010/Hot-100-Retailers |title=''Stores'' 2010 Hot 100 Retailers |publisher=Stores.org|date=August 2017 }}</ref>\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| homepage = {{URL|verizonwireless.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Verizon Wireless'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=3589977|title=Cellco Partnership, Inc.: Private Company Information|last=|first=|date=|website=bloomberg.com|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cellco Partnership d/b/a Verizon Wireless |url=https://www.fcc.gov/document/cellco-partnership-dba-verizon-wireless-0 |website=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |language=en |date=December 16, 2015}}</ref> (commonly shortened to '''Verizon''') is an American telecommunications company which offers [[wireless]] products and services. It is a [[wholly owned subsidiary]] of [[Verizon Communications]]. Verizon Wireless provides service to 154 million subscribers.<ref>https://Verizon.com/about/file/32187/download?token=FxCcxBBC</ref> Verizon Wireless is the second largest [[wireless telecommunications provider]] in the [[United States]] behind [[AT&T]].<ref name=AT&T>{{cite web |title= AT&T Financial Reports & Quarterly Earnings\n|url=https://investors.att.com/~/media/Files/A/ATT-IR/financial-reports/quarterly-earnings/2019/2q-2019/2Q19_Trending_Schedules.pdf> |publisher=AT&T\n|date=July 24, 2019\n|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Verizon Wireless\">{{cite web |title=Financial and Operating Information |url=https://www.verizon.com/about/file/36103/download?token=R4-WHI7h> \n|publisher=Verizon\n|date=June 30, 2019 \n|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}\n</ref><ref name=TheWikipedia>{{cite web |title=List of United States wireless communication providers |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_United_States_wireless_communications_service_providers |publisher=The Wikipedia Community |date=August 1, 2019\n|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}{{Circular reference|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company is headquartered in [[Basking Ridge, New Jersey]]. It was founded in 2000 as a [[joint venture]] of American telecommunications firm [[Bell Atlantic]], which would soon become [[Verizon Communications]], and [[United Kingdom|British]] [[multinational corporation|multinational]] telecommunications company [[Vodafone]].<ref name=\"ReutersApril252013\"/> Verizon Communications became the sole owner in 2014 after buying Vodafone's 45-percent stake in the company.<ref name=\"DeLaMercedSeptember22013\"/>\n\nIt operates a national [[4G]] [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] network covering about 98 percent of the U.S. population,<ref>{{cite web |title=Better Matters|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/landingpages/better-matters/|publisher=Verizon Wireless|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref> which in December 2015 won or tied for top honors in each category of the [[RootMetrics]] RootScore Reports.<ref name=RogerCheng16/> Verizon Wireless offers [[mobile phone]] services through a variety of devices.<ref name=ReutersProfile/> Its LTE in Rural America Program, with 21 rural wireless carriers participating, covers 2.7 million potential users in 169 rural counties.<ref name=PhilGoldstein15-2/> Verizon Wireless announced in 2015 that it was developing a [[5G]], or fifth-generation, network.<ref name=RogerCheng15/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Verizon-Wireless-Logo.svg|thumb|right|Verizon's original logo, used from April 4, 2000, to September 1, 2015. It is still seen on the front of many stores.]]\nIn September 1999, [[United States|American]] [[phone company]] [[Bell Atlantic]] and [[U.K.]]-based [[Vodafone Airtouch PLC]] proposed they would create a new [[mobile phone|wireless phone service]] [[joint venture]] valued at $70 billion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bell Atlantic, Vodafone join wireless services |last1=Noguchi |first1=Yuki |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/pmextra/sept99/21/bellatlantic21.htm |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 21, 1999 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> The joint venture was being created as Bell Atlantic underwent a [[merger]] with [[GTE Corporation]]. In April 2000, the companies announced that the Bell Atlantic\u2013GTE merger would take the name [[Verizon Communications|Verizon]] and that the Bell Atlantic\u2013Vodafone [[wireless]] unit would be called Verizon Wireless (legally Cellco Partnership d/b/a Verizon Wireless).<ref name=\"SchieselApril42000\">{{cite news |title=Bell Atlantic and GTE pick post-merger name |last1=Schiesel |first1=Seth |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/04/business/bell-atlantic-and-gte-pick-post-merger-name.html?gwh=78BBED94BC5A73E64AE5B2BB1599CF45&gwt=pay |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 4, 2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> [[Verizon Communications]] owned 55 percent of Verizon Wireless while Vodafone retained 45 percent ownership.<ref name=\"ReutersApril252013\">{{cite news |title=Timeline: Verizon and Vodafone's long relationship |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/25/us-verizon-vodafone-history-idUSBRE93O19Z20130425 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=April 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Regulators with the [[Federal Communications Commission]] approved the Bell Atlantic\u2013GTE merger on June 16, 2000,<ref name=\"CNNJune162000\">{{cite news |title=Bell, GTE merger approved |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://money.cnn.com/2000/06/16/deals/gte/ |newspaper=[[CNN]] |date=June 16, 2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> creating the largest wireless company in the U.S.<ref name=\"ChenMarch312000\">{{cite news |title=FCC approves wireless-assets merger of Bell Atlantic, Vodafone AirTouch |last1=Chen |first1=Kathy |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB954465877372787351 |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 31, 2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon Wireless held this market position until [[Cingular]] acquired [[AT&T Wireless Services]] in 2004.<ref name=\"RubnerOctober262004\">{{cite news |title=Cingular, AT&T Wireless deal complete, new focus on the horizon |last1=Rubner |first1=Justin |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2004/10/25/daily16.html |newspaper=[[American City Business Journals|Atlanta Business Chronicle]] |date=October 26, 2004 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 2000s, Verizon acquired several wireless phone companies and assets across the country, including West Virginia Wireless in 2006;<ref name=\"CharlestonDailyMailFebruary142007\">{{cite news |title=Business briefs |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.nexis.com/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=4N2F-W4K0-TX4K-931J&csi=8399&oc=00240&perma=true |newspaper=[[Charleston Daily Mail]] |date=February 4, 2007 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Ramcell in 2007;<ref name=\"SalemNewsFebruary182008\">{{cite news |title=Southwestern Oregon to benefit from Verizon Wireless network expansion |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.salem-news.com/articles/february182008/verizon_wireless_2-18-08.php |newspaper=Salem-News.com |date=February 18, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> [[Rural Cellular Corporation]]<ref name=\"DowJonesAugust12008\">{{cite news |title=FCC approves Verizon, Rural Cellular merger |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/djf500/200808010850DOWJONESDJONLINE000579_FORTUNE5.htm |agency=[[Dow Jones Newswires]] |date=August 1, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> and [[SureWest|SureWest Communications]], both in 2008.<ref name=\"FrommerJanuary222008\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless SureWest Wireless biz. Who's next? |last1=Frommer |first1=Dan |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/2008/1/verizon-wireless-buys-surewests-wireless-biz-whos-next  |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Also in 2008, Verizon struck a deal to buy [[Alltel]] for $5.9 billion in equity while assuming $22.2 billion worth of debt.<ref name=\"ReardonJanuary92009\">{{cite news |title=Verizon completes Alltel purchase |last1=Reardon |first1=Marguerite |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-completes-alltel-purchase/  |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=January 9, 2009 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"SorkinJune62008\">{{cite news |title=Verizon agrees to buy Alltel for $28.1 billion |last1=Sorkin |first1=Andrew Ross |last2=Holson |first2=Laura M. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/06/technology/06phone.html  |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> The deal finalized January 9, 2009, again making Verizon Wireless the country's biggest cellphone network.<ref name=\"ReardonJanuary92009\"/> As per the agreement, Verizon sold rural wireless properties across 18 states to AT&T. Those properties were in Alabama, Arizona, California, Colorado, Iowa, Kansas, Michigan, Minnesota, Montana, Nebraska, Nevada, New Mexico, North Dakota, South Dakota, Tennessee, Utah, Virginia and Wyoming.<ref name=\"SvenssonMay92009\">{{cite news |title=AT&T to buy Verizon territories, affecting 1M subscribers |last1=Svensson |first1=Peter |last2= |first2= |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/story?id=7548387 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=May 9, 2009 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon's acquisitions continued in the 2010s, including the purchases of some Plateau Wireless markets in 2012<ref name=\"DanoJune242014\">{{cite news |title=AT&T scoops up 40,000 customers, spectrum assets of Plateau Wireless |last1=Dano |first1=Mike |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/att-scoops-40000-customers-spectrum-assets-plateau-wireless/2014-06-24  |newspaper=FierceWireless.com |date=June 24, 2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> and Golden State Cellular's operator in 2014.<ref name=\"DanoApril212014\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless consumes Golden State Cellular and Mobi PCS |last1=Dano |first1=Mike |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizon-wireless-consumes-golden-state-cellular-and-mobi-pcs/2014-04-21  |newspaper=FierceWireless.com |date=April 21, 2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMajority owner Verizon Communications became sole owner of its wireless business in 2014, when it bought Vodafone's 45 percent stake. Vodafone received $58.9 billion cash, $60.2 billion in stock and $11 billion in other transactions.<ref name=\"DeLaMercedSeptember22013\">{{cite news |title=Verizon seals long-sought $130 billion deal to own wireless unit |last1=De La Merced |first1=Michael J. |last2=Scott |first2=Mark |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/09/02/verizon-reaches-130-billion-deal-to-buy-out-vodafones-wireless-stake/?_r=0 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 2, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"HoltonSeptember22013\">{{cite news |title=Verizon, Vodafone agree to $130 billion wireless deal |last1=Holton |first1=Kate |last2=Carew |first2=Sinead |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/03/us-vodafone-verizon-idUSBRE97S08C20130903 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=September 2, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> An article in [[The New York Times]] estimated Verizon Wireless' valuation at about $290 billion.<ref name=\"DeLaMercedSeptember22013\"/>\n\nIn late 2014, it became known that Verizon Wireless uses [[deep packet inspection]] for server-side insertion of a customer-unique ID field (\"X-UIDH\") into all unencrypted HTTP headers. The mechanism has been referred to as \"[[supercookie]]\" or \"perma-cookie\", although it is not technically a cookie in that it does not store information on the customers device and is transparent to the user. It can not be averted with common mechanisms like ad-blockers; however it can not be inserted into encrypted [[HTTPS]] and [[VPN]] connections. Verizon advertises the system to marketing partners. The [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] has called on Verizon to terminate the program, calling it a \"profound violation of trust\", expressing concern over abuse by third parties, and questioning the legality of Verizon modifying their users' outgoing data without offering them the possibility of a full opt-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/11/verizon-x-uidh|title=Verizon Injecting Perma-Cookies to Track Mobile Customers, Bypassing Privacy Controls|publisher=[[Electronic Frontier Foundation]]|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lessonslearned.org/sniff|title=Checking known AT&T, Verizon, Sprint, Bell Canada & Vodacom Unique Identifier beacons|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/verizon-atandt-tracking-their-users-with-super-cookies/2014/11/03/7bbbf382-6395-11e4-bb14-4cfea1e742d5_story.html|title=Verizon, AT&T tracking their users with 'supercookies'|first=Craig|last=Timberg|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2015/01/which-apps-and-browsers-protect-you-against-verizon-and-turns-non-consensual|title=Which Apps Protect Against Verizon and Turn's Invasive User Tracking?|first=Peter|last=Eckersley|date=January 15, 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/11/att-ditches-tracking-header-program-verizon-still-refuses|title=AT&T Ditches Tracking Header Program; Verizon Still Refuses|first=Jacob|last=Hoffman-Andrews|date=November 14, 2014|publisher=}}</ref> In January 2015, Verizon announced they would give customers the option of opting out, and since April 1, 2015, Verizon has allowed customers to opt-out, either online or by calling a special phone number.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Verizon lets customers opt out of program that inserted 'super cookie' to track mobile browsing|url = http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizon-lets-customers-opt-out-program-inserted-super-cookie-track-mobile-b/2015-04-01|website = FierceWireless|accessdate = May 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Verizon hired [[Ronan Dunne]], the former head of British provider [[O2 (UK)|O2]], as the new president of its wireless business.<ref name=\"bloomberg-vzronan\">{{cite web|title=Verizon Hires Former O2 CEO Ronan Dunne to Head Wireless Unit|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-02/verizon-hires-former-o2-ceo-ronan-dunne-to-head-wireless-unit|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, [[Comcast]] confirmed that it planned to launch a mobile service, using Verizon's network as an [[Mobile Virtual Network Operator|MVNO]], in mid-2017.<ref name=\"verge-comcastmvno\">{{cite web|title=Comcast confirms plans to launch mobile phone service in 2017|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/20/12986872/comcast-mobile-network-verizon-mvno-2017|website=The Verge|date=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Comcast Is Launching a Wireless Service Next Year|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/2016/09/25/comcast-is-launching-a-wireless-service-next-year.aspx|website=The Motley Fool|date=September 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, in the wake of competition from [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] and [[T-Mobile US|T-Mobile]], and initiatives to expand the capacity and improve the quality of its network by using [[macrocell]]s and supporting carrier aggregation, Verizon announced that it would bring back an \"unlimited\" data plan (subject to throttling in heavy network areas after 22&nbsp;GB of usage). Verizon's decision not to restrict the bitrate of video services prompted Sprint and T-Mobile to remove similar restrictions from their own plans.<ref name=\"fortune-unlimitedback\">{{cite web|title=Inside Verizon's Decision to Go Unlimited|url=http://fortune.com/2017/02/23/verizon-unlimited/|website=Fortune|accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Verizon announced that all their Android phones will have AppFlash, to help users find content and services across different apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/28/evie-verizon-sidescreen/|title=Evie teams up with Verizon to launch a new search experience next to your Android home screen|last=Ha|first=Anthony|website=TechCrunch|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> Critics spoke harshly against it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2017/03/28/verizon-phones-will-soon-get-useless-appflash-search-tool-upcoming-rollout/|title=Verizon phones will soon get the useless 'AppFlash' search tool in an upcoming rollout|date=March 28, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2018, Verizon announced that [[Hans Vestberg]] had been picked to become CEO on August 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/08/verizon-exec-vice-president-hans-vestberg-to-become-companys-new-ceo-will-take-over-aug-1.html|title=Verizon picks Hans Vestberg as its next CEO, showing how the company is prioritizing 5G|last=Robins|first=Michael Sheetz, Anjali|date=June 8, 2018|work=CNBC}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, the fire department of [[Santa Clara County, California]], filed evidence in a lawsuit seeking the reinstatement of [[net neutrality]] policies, which accused Verizon of throttling an \"unlimited\" wireless data plan associated with a vehicle that was being used to coordinate responses to the [[Mendocino Complex Fire]]. The department reported that a Verizon Wireless customer service representative insisted that they must upgrade to a higher-cost data plan in order to restore their internet speed. In a statement, Verizon acknowledged that they did not properly explain the terms of their contract, and that the representative did not adhere to a company policy of removing these restrictions during emergency situations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/08/verizon-throttled-fire-departments-unlimited-data-during-calif-wildfire/ |access-date=August 25, 2018 |date=August 21, 2018 |publisher=[[Ars Technica]] |author=Jon Brodkin |title=Verizon throttled fire department's \"unlimited\" data during Calif. wildfire}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Verizon Wireless services were split between two new divisions: Verizon Consumer and [[Verizon Business]].<ref name=\"Keypeople\">{{cite news |title=Verizon to Break Up Wireless Unit in Reorganization |last1=Krouse |first1=Sarah |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-to-break-up-wireless-unit-in-reorganization-1541420253 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=November 5, 2018 |accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Reorg-Reuters\">{{cite news |title=Verizon to reorganize business segments |last1=Dang |first1=Sheila |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-verizon-segments/verizon-to-reorganize-business-segments-idUSKCN1NA1DW |work=[[Reuters]] |date=November 5, 2018 |accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Network==\nVerizon Wireless operates a [[4G]] [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] network, which, {{as of|2016|January|lc=y}}, covers about 98 percent of the U.S.<ref name=TammyParker14>{{cite news |title=Verizon, Sprint lead on delivering mobile data traffic over LTE |last1=Parker |first1=Tammy |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/tech/story/verizon-sprint-lead-delivering-mobile-data-traffic-over-lte/2014-02-23 |newspaper=Fierce Wireless |date=February 23, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> Before their LTE network was launched, they operated an exclusively [[CDMA2000]] network (the other major CDMA2000 carrier in the US being [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]]). Verizon began its initial tests for the 4G LTE network in 2008<ref name=RogerCheng15>{{cite news |title=Verizon to be first to field-test crazy-fast 5G wireless |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-to-hold-worlds-first-crazy-fast-5g-wireless-field-tests-next-year/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=September 8, 2015 |accessdate=January 22, 2016}}</ref> in order to move from older-generation mobile communications technologies to the emerging global standard.<ref name=SaschaSegan15>{{cite news |title=CDMA vs. GSM: What's the difference? |last1=Segan |first1=Sascha |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2407896,00.asp |magazine=[[PC Magazine]] |date=February 6, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> In December 2010, Verizon Wireless launched a fledgling 4G LTE network in 39 markets.<ref name=Reardon10>{{cite news |title=Verizon to launch 4G wireless network December 5 |last1=Reardon |first1=Marguerite |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-to-launch-4g-wireless-network-december-5/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=December 1, 2010 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> By December 2011, only a year after launch, 200 million Americans were covered with 4G LTE, and 190 markets were covered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.verizonwireless.com/news/article/2011/12/pr2011-12-05a.html|title=Happy 1st Anniversary, Verizon Wireless 4G LTE!|website=Verizon Wireless News Center|access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> {{as of|2016}}, 98% of the U.S. is covered with LTE, and 92% of all data traffic is on LTE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.verizon.com/about/investors/quarterly-reports/1q-2016-quarter-earnings-conference-call-webcast|title=1Q 2016 Quarter Earnings Conference Call Webcast|website=www.verizon.com|date=April 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the service provider bought spectrum from the country's biggest cable companies, including [[Comcast]], and [[Spectrum (cable service)|Spectrum]] ([[Time Warner Cable]] and [[Bright House Networks]] at the time) to improve its data network across the U.S.<ref name=\"MikeGikas14\">{{cite news |title=What is Verizon's new high-speed XLTE, and why should I care? |last1=Gikas |first1=Mike |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2014/05/what-is-verizon-4g-xlte/index.htm |newspaper=[[Consumer Reports]] |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> The new capacity allowed Verizon to launch what it calls XLTE (LTE on Band 4) in 2013, providing more capacity in congested and well-populated markets.<ref name=\"BrianChen14\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless Names Faster Part of Its Network: XLTE |last1=Chen |first1=Brian X. |last2= |first2= |url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/verizon-wireless-names-faster-part-of-its-network-xlte/?_r=0 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 19, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBecause 4G LTE is a [[data transmission|data-transmitting]] network, when it launched, Verizon customers' voice calls were still carried over the company's [[CDMA2000]] network,<ref name=\"MargueriteReardon14-2\">{{cite news |title=Verizon set to launch voice-over-LTE service nationwide |last1=Reardon |first1=Marguerite |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-readies-launch-of-nationwide-voice-over-lte-service/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> which was developed for 3G cellphones. In September 2014, Verizon launched [[VoLTE|voice over LTE (VoLTE)]];<ref name=\"PhilGoldstein15\">{{cite news |title=Verizon's Small: We have close to 4M VoLTE customers |last1=Goldstein |first1=Phil |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizons-small-we-have-close-4m-volte-customers/2015-08-11 |newspaper=Fierce Wireless |date=August 11, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> this allowed voice calls to transmit via the data-only LTE network. This also allows for simultaneous voice and data services, something that is unavailable on traditional [[CDMA2000]] calls. Along with VoLTE, Verizon also announced support for [[HDVoice|HD Voice]], which provides higher quality audio for VoLTE calls, and native Video Calling for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones. In March 2016, Verizon enabled support for Wi-Fi Calling, which allows calls to be placed over a Wi-Fi Network. {{as of|2015|August}}, nearly 4 million of Verizon's 103.7 million subscribers used VoLTE.<ref name=\"PhilGoldstein15\" />\n\nA report by [[RootMetrics]] on carrier performance in the first half of 2015 ranked Verizon's network as the best in overall national performance, network reliability, network speed, data performance and call performance.<ref name=MatthewMiller15>{{cite news |title=RootMetrics says Verizon clear leader in wireless performance, T-Mobile CEO furious |last1=Miller |first1=Matthew |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/rootmetrics-report-verizon-the-clear-leader-in-wireless-performance-t-mobiles-john-legere-rants/ |newspaper=[[ZDNet]] |date=August 18, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> For the second half of 2015, RootMetrics's RootScore Report ranked Verizon Wireless No. 1 in overall performance, network speed, network reliability, call performance and data performance.<ref name=RogerCheng16>{{cite news |title=OK, this is the fastest wireless carrier in the nation |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-t-mobile-att-sprint-who-is-the-fastest-carrier-in-the-nation/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=February 17, 2016 |accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> Verizon Wireless and AT&T tied for first in text performance.<ref name=RogerCheng16/>\n\nIn September 2015, Verizon's chief information and technology architect Roger Gurnani stated that Verizon was planning to trial a [[5G]] wireless network within 12 months, with \"some level of commercial deployment\" by 2017.<ref name=RogerCheng15/> In late-August 2016, Verizon officially announced that it had rolled out [[LTE Advanced]] services in 461 markets. The company promoted that the technology would allow at least 50% higher LTE data speeds on supported devices.<ref name=\"verge-ltea\">{{cite web|title=Verizon's faster LTE service is now available in over 450 cities|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/29/12693030/verizon-lte-advanced-461-cities-launched-faster-data-speeds|website=The Verge|date=August 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2019, Verizon had launched 5G service in 30 cities across the U.S.<ref name=\"de Looper19\">{{cite news |title=Verizon reaches goal of 5G in 30 cities in 2019, adds Cleveland and Columbus |last1=de Looper |first1=Christian |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/verizon-5g-rollout/ |work=[[Digital Trends]] |date=December 23, 2019 |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Verizon's 5G network is deployed on [[Extremely_high_frequency|millimeter wave]] spectrum (mmWave).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiercewireless.com/tech/verizon-ceo-defends-mmwave-strategy-for-5g|title=Verizon CEO defends mmWave strategy for 5G|last=Alleven|first=Monica|date=2020-01-30|website=FierceWireless|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> While fast, the high-band spectrum Verizon uses has limited range and high penetration loss.<ref name=\"Sherman20\">{{cite news |title=There are three types of 5G \u2014 most of what you'll get is not the super-fast kind |last1=Sherman |first1=Alex |last2=Haselton |first2=Todd |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/09/what-is-5g-heres-what-verizon-att-sprint-and-t-mobile-offer.html |work=[[CNBC]] |date=January 9, 2020 |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Falahy|first=Naser|last2=Alani|first2=Omar|date=November 2018|title=Millimetre wave frequency band as a candidate spectrum for 5G network architecture: A survey|journal=Physical Communication|language=en|volume=32|pages=120\u2013144|doi=10.1016/j.phycom.2018.11.003}}</ref>\n\n===Radio frequency summary===\n{{further|GSM frequency bands|UMTS frequency bands|LTE frequency bands|NR frequency bands}}\n\nThe following is a list of known 2G, 3G, LTE, and NR frequency bands which Verizon employs in the United States:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Frequency bands used on the Verizon Network\n|-\n! Frequency Band                        !! Band Number !! Protocol !! Generation !! Status !! Notes\n|-\n| '''850'''&nbsp;MHz CLR ||0\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[1xRTT]]/[[EV-DO]]/[[eHRPD]]|| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2G]]/[[3G]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Active/Refarming to 4G LTE<ref name=\"fiercewireless1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/node/162946|title=Verizon to start refarming PCS spectrum for LTE in 2015|last=Marek|first=Sue|date=June 27, 2013|access-date=September 12, 2016|work=FierceWireless}}</ref> || rowspan=\"3\" | Verizon is currently refarming spectrum used for its 2G/3G CDMA networks to 4G LTE in markets where additional LTE capacity is needed; refarming is scheduled be completed by the end of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.commsupdate.com/articles/2019/08/01/verizon-extends-5g-coverage-to-four-more-cities-postpones-3g-shutdown-until-2020/ |title=Verizon extends 5G coverage to four more cities; postpones 3G shutdown until 2020 |website=CommsUpdate |publisher=TeleGeography |date=2019-08-01 |accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''1900'''&nbsp;MHz PCS || 1\n|-\n|'''850'''&nbsp;MHz CLR\n|5|| rowspan=\"4\" | [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] || rowspan=\"4\" | [[4G]]\n|-\n|'''1900'''&nbsp;MHz PCS\n|2\n|Third layer of LTE coverage, used to relieve congestion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phonearena.com/news/Cheat-sheet-which-4G-LTE-bands-do-AT-T-Verizon-T-Mobile-and-Sprint-use-in-the-USA_id77933|title=Cheat sheet: which 4G LTE bands do AT&T, Verizon, T-Mobile and Sprint use in the USA?|last=Hristov|first=Victor|website=Phone Arena|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''700'''&nbsp;MHz Upper C Block || 13 || rowspan=\"2\" | Active ||Main LTE band, completed deployment mid-2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Segan |first=Sascha |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2421046,00.asp |title=Verizon: Nationwide LTE 'Substantially Complete' &#124; News & Opinion |work=PC Magazine |date=June 27, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''1700/2100'''&nbsp;MHz AWS || 4/66 || Branded as \"XLTE\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Alexis|last=Santos|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/10/15/verizons-lte-aws-rollout-begins/|title=Verizon's LTE boosted in 'major markets' by new frequency, hits 80 Mbps down (update) |work=[[Engadget]] |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> at launch, this second layer of LTE coverage is used to increased bandwidth in major markets.\n|-\n| '''28'''&nbsp;GHz mmWave || n257/n261 ||  rowspan=\"2\" | [[5G NR|NR]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[5G]] || rowspan=\"2\" | Active/Building Out || rowspan=\"2\" | mmWave band for high-speed LAA using small cells. Went live in May 2019.\n|-\n| '''39'''&nbsp;GHz mmWave || n260 \n|}{{wide image|Verizon Wireless Store, Norwalk, CT 06854, USA - Feb 2013.jpg|800px|A panoramic view within a Verizon Wireless store, [[Norwalk, Connecticut]], circa February 2013.|alt=A panoramic view within a Verizon Wireless Store, Norwalk, CT, United States}}\n\n==RootMetrics RootScore awards==\n\nVerizon has historically done well on [[RootMetrics]] RootScore Reports.<ref name=Baig16>{{cite news |title=Study: Verizon takes top networking honors |last1=Baig |first1=Edward |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/baig/2016/02/18/study-verizon-takes-top-networking-honors/80522048/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=February 18, 2016 |accessdate=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ RootMetrics US national RootScore reports<ref name=RootScore15>{{cite web |url=http://www.rootmetrics.com/en-US/rootscore/map/national/united-states/2015/2H |title=RootScore Awards |author= |date=2016 |publisher=RootMetrics |accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref>\n! Report Date\n! Overall Performance rank\n! Call Performance rank\n! Text Performance rank\n! Data Performance rank\n! Network Speed rank\n! Network Reliability rank\n|-\n! 2nd Half\n2013\n| rowspan=\"13\" | '''1st Place'''\n| rowspan=\"13\" |'''1st Place'''\n| '''1st Place'''\n| rowspan=\"13\" |'''1st Place'''\n| 2nd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n| rowspan=\"13\" | '''1st Place'''\n|-\n! 1st Half\n2014\n| 2nd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n| rowspan=\"12\" |'''1st Place'''\n|-\n! 2nd Half\n2014\n| 3rd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]], #2: [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]])\n|-\n! 1st Half\n2015\n| 2nd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n|-\n! 2nd Half\n2015\n| '''1st Place'''\n(Tied #1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n|-\n!1st Half\n2016\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''1st Place'''\n|-\n!2nd Half\n2016\n|-\n!1st Half\n2017\n|'''1st Place'''\n(Tied #1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]], [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]])\n|- \n!2nd Half\n2017\n|'''1st Place''' (Tied #1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]], [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]])\n|-\n!1st Half\n2018\n| rowspan=\"4\" |'''1st Place''' (Tied #1: [[AT&T]])\n|-\n!2nd Half\n2018\n|-\n!1st Half\n2019\n|-\n!2nd Half 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rootmetrics.com/en-US/content/us-state-of-the-mobile-union-2h-2019|title=US State of the Mobile Union: carrier performance at national, state, and metro levels 2H 2019|last=Anderson|first=Dave|date=2020-01-28|website=RootMetrics|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n== Apps ==\nVerizon Wireless offers certain applications and services that are exclusive to its subscribers. Many of these [[mobile app|apps]] are pre-loaded on Verizon devices\u2014primarily [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphones. The company has received criticism for this practice, as users and critics have viewed the applications to be [[Pre-installed software|\"bloatware\"]] that are sometimes redundant to applications already included with the device's operating system.<ref name=\"laptop-s5remove\">{{cite web|title=Samsung Galaxy S5 Bloatware Removal Guide|url=http://blog.laptopmag.com/galaxy-s5-bloatware-list|website=Laptop Magazine|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=wired-androidbloatware>{{cite journal|title=Bloatware Creeps Into Android Phones|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/07/bloatware-android-phones/|journal=Wired|date=July 22, 2010}}</ref><ref name=time-sorrierstate>{{cite web|title=Friday Rant: The Ever-Sorrier State of Android Bloatware|url=http://time.com/94646/android-bloatware/|website=Time|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe NFL Mobile app allows Verizon Wireless subscribers to stream [[National Football League]] games and [[NFL Network]] on their devices. While previously a subscription-based service, NFL Mobile was made free to all subscribers beginning in the [[2015 NFL season]]. As part of an exclusivity agreement with the NFL, only Verizon Wireless subscribers could stream NFL telecasts to devices with screens {{convert|7|in|cm}} or less in size. This contract ended after the [[2017 NFL season]];<ref name=exclusive/><ref name=variety12616>{{cite web|title=CBS Tackles New Game With Super Bowl 50: Digital Viewers And Live-Streamed Ads|work=Variety|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=January 28, 2016|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/super-bowl-commercials-cbs-live-streaming-digital-1201688878/}}</ref><ref name=\"cbs-where\">{{cite web|title=Super Bowl 2016: How to watch Super Bowl 50 on TV, online on CBS|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25438861/how-to-watch-super-bowl-50-on-tv-online-and-halftime-show-information|publisher=CBSSports.com|accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SpranglerSeptember42015\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless Drops $5 Monthly Fee to Watch NFL Live Games for All Customers |last1=Spangler |first1=Todd |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/business/20150903_Reuters_MT1VRT1201585307_Verizon_Wireless_Drops__5_Monthly_Fee_to_Watch_NFL_Live_Games_for_All_Customers.html  |agency=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 4, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon agreed to a new five-year, non-exclusive digital rights agreement, which removes the device class exclusivity, and focuses more upon distributing its streams and other enhanced digital content via its [[Oath Inc.|portfolio of internet media brands]], rather than being exclusive to Verizon Wireless subscribers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/21737823/verizon-nfl-agree-new-5-year-deal-worth-nearly-25-billion|title=Verizon, NFL agree to new 5-year deal worth nearly $2.5 billion|first=Darren|last=Rovell|work=ESPN.com|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=exclusive>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2017/10/23/Leagues-and-Governing-Bodies/NFL-notes.aspx|title=Verizon's exclusivity for live games on mobile expected to end|website=Sports Business Daily|language=en-US|date=October 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs part of a deal that also granted the carrier [[title sponsor]]ship of the series, Verizon subscribers also have access to exclusive streaming content within the official [[IndyCar Series]] app.<ref name=\"CardenasMay242015\">{{cite news |title=App brings IndyCar racing from the track to mobile devices |last1=Cardenas |first1=Edward |last2= |first2= |url=http://detroit.cbslocal.com/2015/05/24/app-brings-indycar-racing-from-the-track-to-mobile-devices/ |work=CBSDetroit.com |date=May 24, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe My Verizon app is used for account management, including checking usage statistics and managing the user's service plan and account features.<ref name=\"usatoday-newplans16\">{{cite web|title=Verizon's new plans raise prices for more data|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2016/07/06/amid-growing-competition-verizon-revamps-data-plans/86755334/|website=USA Today|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"KomandoSeptember222014\">{{cite web |url=http://www.komando.com/apps/273517/verizon-app-see-usage-network-performance-set-limits-and-more |title=Verizon App: See usage, network performance, set limits and more |author=Komando staff |date=September 22, 2014 |work=[[Kim Komando|Kommando.com]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813232230/http://www.komando.com/apps/273517/verizon-app-see-usage-network-performance-set-limits-and-more |archive-date=August 13, 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"BereznakOctober242014\">{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/tech/how-to-lock-down-your-data-usage-once-and-for-all-100825489429.html |title=How to lock down your data usage once and for all |first=Alyssa|last=Bereznak |date=October 24, 2014 |work=[[Yahoo!]] Tech |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon Cloud, which allows photos, videos, contacts, messages and call logs to be synchronized online, was released in April 2013 initially for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones,<ref name=\"FingasApril292013\">{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/04/29/verizon-cloud-backup-app-rolling-out-for-android-coming-to-ios/ |title=Verizon Cloud backup service rolling out for Android, comes soon to iOS |first=Jon|last=Fingas |date=April 29, 2013 |work=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> followed the next month by a launch for [[iOS]].<ref name=\"FingasApril292013\"/><ref name=\"WhitneyMay242013\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-cloud-adds-online-storage-for-ios-devices/ |title=Verizon Cloud adds online storage for iOS devices |first=Lance|last=Whitney |date=May 24, 2013 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WhitneyMay242013\"/>  Verizon Messages, otherwise known as Message+, is an alternative [[text messaging]] app that additionally allows messages to be synchronized between multiple devices.<ref name=\"MusilMarch212013\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/new-verizon-app-untethers-text-messages-from-your-cell-phone/ |title=New Verizon app untethers text messages from your cell phone |first=Steven|last=Musil |date=March 21, 2013 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> VZ Navigator is a subscription-based [[map]]s and [[navigation]] service which provides [[turn-by-turn navigation]], [[crowdsourcing|crowdsourced]] [[traffic]] [[data]], weather, events and entertainment listings, gas prices, roadside assistance, 2D and 3D views.<ref name=\"LendinoMarch232010\">{{cite news |title=VZ Navigator 5 review |last1=Lendino |first1=Jamie |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2361689,00.asp |magazine=[[PC Magazine]] |date=March 23, 2010 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> The Verizon Support & Protection app provides technical support services, lost device location, and on Android, antivirus functionality.<ref name=\"ChuangFebruary232015\">{{cite news |title=Mailbag: Most Internet providers offer antivirus software for free |last1=Chuang |first1=Tamara |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.denverpost.com/techmailbag/ci_27569296/mailbag-most-internet-providers-offer-antivirus-software-free |newspaper=[[The Denver Post]] |date=February 23, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVerizon Family Locator is a subscription-based service and app can be used to track the locations of family members on a map for up to 10 devices.<ref name=\"RosenbloomJune132013\">{{cite news |title=Where is everyone? Try a tracking app |last1=Rosenbloom |first1=Stephanie |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/16/travel/where-is-everyone-try-a-tracking-app.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=WebsterJune242013>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/six-ways-to-share-your-exact-location-with-family-and-why/ |title=Six ways to share your exact location with family (and why) |first=Scott|last=Webster |date=June 24, 2013 |publisher=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon Family Base allows parents to restrict when and how their children use their phones, view their children's contacts and lock the devices.<ref name=\"WebsterJune242013\"/><ref name=\"ChengFebruary132014\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/so-is-verizons-more-everything-plan-a-good-deal/ |title=So is Verizon's 'More Everything' plan a good deal? |first=Roger|last=Cheng |date=February 13, 2014 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon also offers the GizmoPal, a wristband-worn phone for children that is restricted to only placing or receiving calls from one of two designated caregivers, and has [[GPS tracking unit|GPS tracking]].<ref name=\"AlvarezNovember262014\">{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/11/26/lg-gizmopal-verizon/ |title=LG GizmoPal wearable lets kids call their parents with one button |first=Edgar|last=Alvarez |date=November 26, 2014 |work=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"SeganJanuary302015\">{{cite news |title=LG GizmoPal (Verizon Wireless) |last1=Segan |first1=Sascha |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2475924,00.asp |newspaper=[[PC Magazine]] |date=January 30, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther Verizon Wireless apps include Field Force Manager, which allows employers to manage employees with GPS, management timesheets and oversee travel,<ref name=\"BreedenJune52014\">{{cite web |url=http://gcn.com/articles/2014/06/05/cheektowaga-xora.aspx |title=GPS, geofencing drive highway department efficiency |author=John Breeden II |date=June 5, 2014 |publisher=GCN |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Visual Voice Mail<ref name=\"BradleyDecember312014\">{{cite news |title=Crucial features iPhone users just take for granted |last1=Bradley |first1=Tony |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tonybradley/2014/12/31/crucial-features-iphone-users-just-take-for-granted/ |newspaper=[[Forbes]] |date=December 31, 2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> and Roadside Assistance.<ref name=\"HarrisDemandMedia\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless and Roadside Assistance |last1=Harris |first1=Brad |last2= |first2= |url=http://smallbusiness.chron.com/verizon-wireless-roadside-assistance-27324.html  |agency=[[Demand Media]] |date= |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ColleyJuly202012\">{{cite news |title=5 ways to get cheap (or even free) roadside assistance |last1=Colley |first1=Angela |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/Saving-Money/2012/0720/5-ways-to-get-cheap-or-even-free-roadside-assistance |newspaper=[[Christian Science Monitor]] |date=July 20, 2012 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Products and services==\nVerizon Wireless offers mobile phone, home telephone, and Internet services through a variety of devices.\n\n===Wireless phone services===\nVerizon Wireless offers smartphones powered by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iOS]], [[Google]]'s [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Microsoft]]'s [[Windows Phone]] and [[BlackBerry OS]].<ref name=ReutersProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/companyProfile?symbol=VZ.N |title=Profile: Verizon Communications Inc. |author= |date= |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate= February 4, 2016}}</ref> Both its [[Feature phone|basic phones]] and smartphones use their 4G LTE network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashgear.com/verizon-launches-its-first-4g-lte-basic-phone-16488613/|title=Verizon launches its first 4G LTE basic phone|date=2017-06-16|website=SlashGear|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> The company offers different voice and data plans for its users.<ref name=ChloeAlbanesius>{{cite news |title=New Verizon plans ditch phone subsidies, contracts |last1=Albanesius |first1=Chloe |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2489253,00.asp |newspaper=[[PC Magazine]] |date=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=RogerCheng>{{cite news |title=Verizon kills off service contracts, smartphone subsidies |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-kills-off-service-contracts-smartphone-subsidies/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Wireless home phone===\nIntroduced in February 2015 as Verizon Wireless Home Phone Connect, Wireless Home Phone uses Verizon's cellular network rather than using traditional landline wires to provide home phone service.<ref name=RyanKnutson>{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless gets a boost from home phones \u2014 yes, home phones |last1=Knutson |first1=Ryan |last2= |first2= |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2014/04/24/verizon-wireless-gets-a-boost-from-home-phones-yes-home-phones/ |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=April 24, 2014 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Mobile Wi-Fi and broadband===\nVerizon Wireless sells Wi-Fi hotspot devices, branded as Jetpack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/support/verizon-jetpack-faqs/|title=Verizon Jetpack FAQs - Mobile Hotspot|website=www.verizonwireless.com|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The company offered home Internet service through a 4G LTE Broadband Router with Voice that can connect up to 10 devices over Wi-Fi as well as home phone service.<ref name=RogerCheng092513>{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless nudges into home phone, broadband biz |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-wireless-nudges-into-home-phone-broadband-biz/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref> This service and device have since been discontinued.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/home-office-solutions/verizon-lte-internet-and-home-phone/|title=Verizon LTE Internet and Home Phone|website=Verizon Wireless|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==LTE in Rural America<span id=\"LRA\"></span>==\nThe LTE in Rural America Program (or LRA program), introduced in May 2010, covers 2.7 million potential users over {{convert|225000|mi2|km2|}} in 169 rural counties.<ref name=PhilGoldstein15-2>{{cite news |title=Verizon: All 21 LTE in Rural America carrier partners have launched service |last1=Goldstein |first1=Phil |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizon-all-21-lte-rural-america-carrier-partners-have-launched-service/2015-10-15 |newspaper=Fierce Wireless |date=October 15, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> Under this program, partners lease spectrum from Verizon Wireless and connect to the company's network, and Verizon provides technical support and resources to help the rural wireless company build out its own 4G LTE network. The program extends the footprint of 4G LTE coverage for both the rural carrier and Verizon, as customers can take advantage of both networks.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Verizon's LTE in Rural America (LRA) Program Celebrates Five Years of Delivering Advanced Wireless Services to Rural Customers|url = http://www.verizonwireless.com/news/article/2015/05/verizons-lte-in-rural-america-lra-program-celebrates-five-years-of-delivering-advanced-wireless-services-to-rural-customers.html|website = Verizon Wireless News Center|accessdate = May 20, 2015}}</ref> {{as of|2015}}, all LRA members have fully rolled out their 4G LTE networks. \n\nCarriers who participated in the program are:\n\n* Appalachian Wireless\n* Bluegrass Cellular\n* Carolina West Wireless\n* [[Cellcom (United States)|Cellcom]]\n* Chariton Valley\n* Chat Mobility\n* Copper Valley Telecom\n* Bravado Wireless (former Sprocket Wireless by Cross Telephone)\n* Custer Telephone Cooperative\n* Ketchikan Public Utilities\n* Nemont\n* NorthwestCell\n* Pioneer Cellular\n* STRATA Networks\n* Southwestern Wireless (formerly Key Communications)\n* S & R Communications\n* Thumb Cellular\n* Triangle Mobile\n* Wireless Partners\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of mobile phone standards]]\n* [[GreatCall]]\n* [[Librestream]]\n* [[Page Plus Cellular]]\n* [[Venturi Transport Protocol]]\n* [[Vodafone#The Americas|Vodafone in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.verizonwireless.com Official website]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000519214314/http://www.verizonwireless.com/ |date=May 19, 2000 |title=Verizon Wireless }}\n\n{{Verizon Wireless}}\n{{Verizon}}\n{{US mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Verizon Wireless| ]]\n[[Category:Verizon Communications|Wireless]]\n[[Category:Vodafone]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Somerset County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Bernards Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Multinational joint-venture companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|US telecommunications company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| trade_name = Verizon Wireless\n| logo = Verizon 2015 logo -vector.svg\n| logo_caption = Verizon's current logo as of September 1, 2015\n| alt = The text \"verizon\" with a red check mark to the right of it\n| type = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| industry = [[Telecommunication]]s\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2000|04|04}} in [[Bedminster, New Jersey|Bedminster]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| founder = [[Vodafone]]<br>[[Bell Atlantic]]\n| location_city = [[Basking Ridge, New Jersey]]\n| locations = 2,330 owned retail stores\n| area_served = United States\n| key_people = [[Hans Vestberg]]<br><small>(CEO, Verizon Communications)</small><br>[[Ronan Dunne]]<br><small> (CEO, Verizon Consumer)</small>\n| services = [[Mobile telephony]]<br>[[Wireless broadband]]\n| parent = \n| owner = [[Verizon Communications]]\n| footnotes = <ref name=\"ver_corp_hist\">{{cite web|url=http://investor.verizon.com/profile/history/|title=The History of Verizon Communications|work=Verizon Wireless|accessdate=May 7, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"VerizonWireless.com\">{{cite web|url=http://aboutus.verizonwireless.com/leadership/executive/index.html |title=Executive Leadership |publisher=Aboutus.verizonwireless.com |accessdate=May 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stores.org/2010/Hot-100-Retailers |title=''Stores'' 2010 Hot 100 Retailers |publisher=Stores.org|date=August 2017 }}</ref>\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| homepage = {{URL|verizonwireless.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Verizon Wireless''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=3589977|title=Cellco Partnership, Inc.: Private Company Information|last=|first=|date=|website=bloomberg.com|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cellco Partnership d/b/a Verizon Wireless |url=https://www.fcc.gov/document/cellco-partnership-dba-verizon-wireless-0 |website=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |language=en |date=December 16, 2015}}</ref> (commonly shortened to '''Verizon''') is an American telecommunications company which offers [[wireless]] products and services. It is a [[wholly owned subsidiary]] of [[Verizon Communications]]. Verizon Wireless provides service to 154 million subscribers.<ref>https://Verizon.com/about/file/32187/download?token=FxCcxBBC</ref> Verizon Wireless is the second largest [[wireless telecommunications provider]] in the [[United States]] behind [[AT&T]].<ref name=AT&T>{{cite web |title= AT&T Financial Reports & Quarterly Earnings\n|url=https://investors.att.com/~/media/Files/A/ATT-IR/financial-reports/quarterly-earnings/2019/2q-2019/2Q19_Trending_Schedules.pdf> |publisher=AT&T\n|date=July 24, 2019\n|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Verizon Wireless\">{{cite web |title=Financial and Operating Information |url=https://www.verizon.com/about/file/36103/download?token=R4-WHI7h> \n|publisher=Verizon\n|date=June 30, 2019 \n|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}\n</ref><ref name=TheWikipedia>{{cite web |title=List of United States wireless communication providers |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_United_States_wireless_communications_service_providers |publisher=The Wikipedia Community |date=August 1, 2019\n|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}{{Circular reference|date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company is headquartered in [[Basking Ridge, New Jersey]]. It was founded in 2000 as a [[joint venture]] of American telecommunications firm [[Bell Atlantic]], which would soon become [[Verizon Communications]], and [[United Kingdom|British]] [[multinational corporation|multinational]] telecommunications company [[Vodafone]].<ref name=\"ReutersApril252013\"/> Verizon Communications became the sole owner in 2014 after buying Vodafone's 45-percent stake in the company.<ref name=\"DeLaMercedSeptember22013\"/>\n\nIt operates a national [[4G]] [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] network covering about 98 percent of the U.S. population,<ref>{{cite web |title=Better Matters|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/landingpages/better-matters/|publisher=Verizon Wireless|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref> which in December 2015 won or tied for top honors in each category of the [[RootMetrics]] RootScore Reports.<ref name=RogerCheng16/> Verizon Wireless offers [[mobile phone]] services through a variety of devices.<ref name=ReutersProfile/> Its LTE in Rural America Program, with 21 rural wireless carriers participating, covers 2.7 million potential users in 169 rural counties.<ref name=PhilGoldstein15-2/> Verizon Wireless announced in 2015 that it was developing a [[5G]], or fifth-generation, network.<ref name=RogerCheng15/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Verizon-Wireless-Logo.svg|thumb|right|Verizon's original logo, used from April 4, 2000, to September 1, 2015. It is still seen on the front of many stores.]]\nIn September 1999, [[United States|American]] [[phone company]] [[Bell Atlantic]] and [[U.K.]]-based [[Vodafone Airtouch PLC]] proposed they would create a new [[mobile phone|wireless phone service]] [[joint venture]] valued at $70 billion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bell Atlantic, Vodafone join wireless services |last1=Noguchi |first1=Yuki |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/pmextra/sept99/21/bellatlantic21.htm |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 21, 1999 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> The joint venture was being created as Bell Atlantic underwent a [[merger]] with [[GTE Corporation]]. In April 2000, the companies announced that the Bell Atlantic\u2013GTE merger would take the name [[Verizon Communications|Verizon]] and that the Bell Atlantic\u2013Vodafone [[wireless]] unit would be called Verizon Wireless (legally Cellco Partnership d/b/a Verizon Wireless).<ref name=\"SchieselApril42000\">{{cite news |title=Bell Atlantic and GTE pick post-merger name |last1=Schiesel |first1=Seth |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/04/business/bell-atlantic-and-gte-pick-post-merger-name.html?gwh=78BBED94BC5A73E64AE5B2BB1599CF45&gwt=pay |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 4, 2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> [[Verizon Communications]] owned 55 percent of Verizon Wireless while Vodafone retained 45 percent ownership.<ref name=\"ReutersApril252013\">{{cite news |title=Timeline: Verizon and Vodafone's long relationship |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/25/us-verizon-vodafone-history-idUSBRE93O19Z20130425 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=April 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Regulators with the [[Federal Communications Commission]] approved the Bell Atlantic\u2013GTE merger on June 16, 2000,<ref name=\"CNNJune162000\">{{cite news |title=Bell, GTE merger approved |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://money.cnn.com/2000/06/16/deals/gte/ |newspaper=[[CNN]] |date=June 16, 2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> creating the largest wireless company in the U.S.<ref name=\"ChenMarch312000\">{{cite news |title=FCC approves wireless-assets merger of Bell Atlantic, Vodafone AirTouch |last1=Chen |first1=Kathy |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB954465877372787351 |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 31, 2000 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon Wireless held this market position until [[Cingular]] acquired [[AT&T Wireless Services]] in 2004.<ref name=\"RubnerOctober262004\">{{cite news |title=Cingular, AT&T Wireless deal complete, new focus on the horizon |last1=Rubner |first1=Justin |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2004/10/25/daily16.html |newspaper=[[American City Business Journals|Atlanta Business Chronicle]] |date=October 26, 2004 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 2000s, Verizon acquired several wireless phone companies and assets across the country, including West Virginia Wireless in 2006;<ref name=\"CharlestonDailyMailFebruary142007\">{{cite news |title=Business briefs |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.nexis.com/docview/getDocForCuiReq?lni=4N2F-W4K0-TX4K-931J&csi=8399&oc=00240&perma=true |newspaper=[[Charleston Daily Mail]] |date=February 4, 2007 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Ramcell in 2007;<ref name=\"SalemNewsFebruary182008\">{{cite news |title=Southwestern Oregon to benefit from Verizon Wireless network expansion |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.salem-news.com/articles/february182008/verizon_wireless_2-18-08.php |newspaper=Salem-News.com |date=February 18, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> [[Rural Cellular Corporation]]<ref name=\"DowJonesAugust12008\">{{cite news |title=FCC approves Verizon, Rural Cellular merger |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |url=http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/djf500/200808010850DOWJONESDJONLINE000579_FORTUNE5.htm |agency=[[Dow Jones Newswires]] |date=August 1, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> and [[SureWest|SureWest Communications]], both in 2008.<ref name=\"FrommerJanuary222008\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless SureWest Wireless biz. Who's next? |last1=Frommer |first1=Dan |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/2008/1/verizon-wireless-buys-surewests-wireless-biz-whos-next  |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Also in 2008, Verizon struck a deal to buy [[Alltel]] for $5.9 billion in equity while assuming $22.2 billion worth of debt.<ref name=\"ReardonJanuary92009\">{{cite news |title=Verizon completes Alltel purchase |last1=Reardon |first1=Marguerite |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-completes-alltel-purchase/  |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=January 9, 2009 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"SorkinJune62008\">{{cite news |title=Verizon agrees to buy Alltel for $28.1 billion |last1=Sorkin |first1=Andrew Ross |last2=Holson |first2=Laura M. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/06/technology/06phone.html  |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> The deal finalized January 9, 2009, again making Verizon Wireless the country's biggest cellphone network.<ref name=\"ReardonJanuary92009\"/> As per the agreement, Verizon sold rural wireless properties across 18 states to AT&T. Those properties were in Alabama, Arizona, California, Colorado, Iowa, Kansas, Michigan, Minnesota, Montana, Nebraska, Nevada, New Mexico, North Dakota, South Dakota, Tennessee, Utah, Virginia and Wyoming.<ref name=\"SvenssonMay92009\">{{cite news |title=AT&T to buy Verizon territories, affecting 1M subscribers |last1=Svensson |first1=Peter |last2= |first2= |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/story?id=7548387 |agency=[[The Associated Press]] |date=May 9, 2009 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon's acquisitions continued in the 2010s, including the purchases of some Plateau Wireless markets in 2012<ref name=\"DanoJune242014\">{{cite news |title=AT&T scoops up 40,000 customers, spectrum assets of Plateau Wireless |last1=Dano |first1=Mike |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/att-scoops-40000-customers-spectrum-assets-plateau-wireless/2014-06-24  |newspaper=FierceWireless.com |date=June 24, 2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> and Golden State Cellular's operator in 2014.<ref name=\"DanoApril212014\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless consumes Golden State Cellular and Mobi PCS |last1=Dano |first1=Mike |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizon-wireless-consumes-golden-state-cellular-and-mobi-pcs/2014-04-21  |newspaper=FierceWireless.com |date=April 21, 2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMajority owner Verizon Communications became sole owner of its wireless business in 2014, when it bought Vodafone's 45 percent stake. Vodafone received $58.9 billion cash, $60.2 billion in stock and $11 billion in other transactions.<ref name=\"DeLaMercedSeptember22013\">{{cite news |title=Verizon seals long-sought $130 billion deal to own wireless unit |last1=De La Merced |first1=Michael J. |last2=Scott |first2=Mark |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/09/02/verizon-reaches-130-billion-deal-to-buy-out-vodafones-wireless-stake/?_r=0 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 2, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"HoltonSeptember22013\">{{cite news |title=Verizon, Vodafone agree to $130 billion wireless deal |last1=Holton |first1=Kate |last2=Carew |first2=Sinead |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/03/us-vodafone-verizon-idUSBRE97S08C20130903 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=September 2, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> An article in [[The New York Times]] estimated Verizon Wireless' valuation at about $290 billion.<ref name=\"DeLaMercedSeptember22013\"/>\n\nIn late 2014, it became known that Verizon Wireless uses [[deep packet inspection]] for server-side insertion of a customer-unique ID field (\"X-UIDH\") into all unencrypted HTTP headers. The mechanism has been referred to as \"[[supercookie]]\" or \"perma-cookie\", although it is not technically a cookie in that it does not store information on the customers device and is transparent to the user. It can not be averted with common mechanisms like ad-blockers; however it can not be inserted into encrypted [[HTTPS]] and [[VPN]] connections. Verizon advertises the system to marketing partners. The [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]] has called on Verizon to terminate the program, calling it a \"profound violation of trust\", expressing concern over abuse by third parties, and questioning the legality of Verizon modifying their users' outgoing data without offering them the possibility of a full opt-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/11/verizon-x-uidh|title=Verizon Injecting Perma-Cookies to Track Mobile Customers, Bypassing Privacy Controls|publisher=[[Electronic Frontier Foundation]]|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lessonslearned.org/sniff|title=Checking known AT&T, Verizon, Sprint, Bell Canada & Vodacom Unique Identifier beacons|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/verizon-atandt-tracking-their-users-with-super-cookies/2014/11/03/7bbbf382-6395-11e4-bb14-4cfea1e742d5_story.html|title=Verizon, AT&T tracking their users with 'supercookies'|first=Craig|last=Timberg|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2015/01/which-apps-and-browsers-protect-you-against-verizon-and-turns-non-consensual|title=Which Apps Protect Against Verizon and Turn's Invasive User Tracking?|first=Peter|last=Eckersley|date=January 15, 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/11/att-ditches-tracking-header-program-verizon-still-refuses|title=AT&T Ditches Tracking Header Program; Verizon Still Refuses|first=Jacob|last=Hoffman-Andrews|date=November 14, 2014|publisher=}}</ref> In January 2015, Verizon announced they would give customers the option of opting out, and since April 1, 2015, Verizon has allowed customers to opt-out, either online or by calling a special phone number.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Verizon lets customers opt out of program that inserted 'super cookie' to track mobile browsing|url = http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizon-lets-customers-opt-out-program-inserted-super-cookie-track-mobile-b/2015-04-01|website = FierceWireless|accessdate = May 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, Verizon hired [[Ronan Dunne]], the former head of British provider [[O2 (UK)|O2]], as the new president of its wireless business.<ref name=\"bloomberg-vzronan\">{{cite web|title=Verizon Hires Former O2 CEO Ronan Dunne to Head Wireless Unit|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-02/verizon-hires-former-o2-ceo-ronan-dunne-to-head-wireless-unit|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, [[Comcast]] confirmed that it planned to launch a mobile service, using Verizon's network as an [[Mobile Virtual Network Operator|MVNO]], in mid-2017.<ref name=\"verge-comcastmvno\">{{cite web|title=Comcast confirms plans to launch mobile phone service in 2017|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/20/12986872/comcast-mobile-network-verizon-mvno-2017|website=The Verge|date=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Comcast Is Launching a Wireless Service Next Year|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/2016/09/25/comcast-is-launching-a-wireless-service-next-year.aspx|website=The Motley Fool|date=September 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, in the wake of competition from [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] and [[T-Mobile US|T-Mobile]], and initiatives to expand the capacity and improve the quality of its network by using [[macrocell]]s and supporting carrier aggregation, Verizon announced that it would bring back an \"unlimited\" data plan (subject to throttling in heavy network areas after 22&nbsp;GB of usage). Verizon's decision not to restrict the bitrate of video services prompted Sprint and T-Mobile to remove similar restrictions from their own plans.<ref name=\"fortune-unlimitedback\">{{cite web|title=Inside Verizon's Decision to Go Unlimited|url=http://fortune.com/2017/02/23/verizon-unlimited/|website=Fortune|accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Verizon announced that all their Android phones will have AppFlash, to help users find content and services across different apps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/28/evie-verizon-sidescreen/|title=Evie teams up with Verizon to launch a new search experience next to your Android home screen|last=Ha|first=Anthony|website=TechCrunch|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> Critics spoke harshly against it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2017/03/28/verizon-phones-will-soon-get-useless-appflash-search-tool-upcoming-rollout/|title=Verizon phones will soon get the useless 'AppFlash' search tool in an upcoming rollout|date=March 28, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2018, Verizon announced that [[Hans Vestberg]] had been picked to become CEO on August 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/08/verizon-exec-vice-president-hans-vestberg-to-become-companys-new-ceo-will-take-over-aug-1.html|title=Verizon picks Hans Vestberg as its next CEO, showing how the company is prioritizing 5G|last=Robins|first=Michael Sheetz, Anjali|date=June 8, 2018|work=CNBC}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, the fire department of [[Santa Clara County, California]], filed evidence in a lawsuit seeking the reinstatement of [[net neutrality]] policies, which accused Verizon of throttling an \"unlimited\" wireless data plan associated with a vehicle that was being used to coordinate responses to the [[Mendocino Complex Fire]]. The department reported that a Verizon Wireless customer service representative insisted that they must upgrade to a higher-cost data plan in order to restore their internet speed. In a statement, Verizon acknowledged that they did not properly explain the terms of their contract, and that the representative did not adhere to a company policy of removing these restrictions during emergency situations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/08/verizon-throttled-fire-departments-unlimited-data-during-calif-wildfire/ |access-date=August 25, 2018 |date=August 21, 2018 |publisher=[[Ars Technica]] |author=Jon Brodkin |title=Verizon throttled fire department's \"unlimited\" data during Calif. wildfire}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Verizon Wireless services were split between two new divisions: Verizon Consumer and [[Verizon Business]].<ref name=\"Keypeople\">{{cite news |title=Verizon to Break Up Wireless Unit in Reorganization |last1=Krouse |first1=Sarah |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-to-break-up-wireless-unit-in-reorganization-1541420253 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=November 5, 2018 |accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Reorg-Reuters\">{{cite news |title=Verizon to reorganize business segments |last1=Dang |first1=Sheila |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-verizon-segments/verizon-to-reorganize-business-segments-idUSKCN1NA1DW |work=[[Reuters]] |date=November 5, 2018 |accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Network==\nVerizon Wireless operates a [[4G]] [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] network, which, {{as of|2016|January|lc=y}}, covers about 98 percent of the U.S.<ref name=TammyParker14>{{cite news |title=Verizon, Sprint lead on delivering mobile data traffic over LTE |last1=Parker |first1=Tammy |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/tech/story/verizon-sprint-lead-delivering-mobile-data-traffic-over-lte/2014-02-23 |newspaper=Fierce Wireless |date=February 23, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> Before their LTE network was launched, they operated an exclusively [[CDMA2000]] network (the other major CDMA2000 carrier in the US being [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]]). Verizon began its initial tests for the 4G LTE network in 2008<ref name=RogerCheng15>{{cite news |title=Verizon to be first to field-test crazy-fast 5G wireless |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-to-hold-worlds-first-crazy-fast-5g-wireless-field-tests-next-year/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=September 8, 2015 |accessdate=January 22, 2016}}</ref> in order to move from older-generation mobile communications technologies to the emerging global standard.<ref name=SaschaSegan15>{{cite news |title=CDMA vs. GSM: What's the difference? |last1=Segan |first1=Sascha |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2407896,00.asp |magazine=[[PC Magazine]] |date=February 6, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> In December 2010, Verizon Wireless launched a fledgling 4G LTE network in 39 markets.<ref name=Reardon10>{{cite news |title=Verizon to launch 4G wireless network December 5 |last1=Reardon |first1=Marguerite |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-to-launch-4g-wireless-network-december-5/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=December 1, 2010 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> By December 2011, only a year after launch, 200 million Americans were covered with 4G LTE, and 190 markets were covered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.verizonwireless.com/news/article/2011/12/pr2011-12-05a.html|title=Happy 1st Anniversary, Verizon Wireless 4G LTE!|website=Verizon Wireless News Center|access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> {{as of|2016}}, 98% of the U.S. is covered with LTE, and 92% of all data traffic is on LTE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.verizon.com/about/investors/quarterly-reports/1q-2016-quarter-earnings-conference-call-webcast|title=1Q 2016 Quarter Earnings Conference Call Webcast|website=www.verizon.com|date=April 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the service provider bought spectrum from the country's biggest cable companies, including [[Comcast]], and [[Spectrum (cable service)|Spectrum]] ([[Time Warner Cable]] and [[Bright House Networks]] at the time) to improve its data network across the U.S.<ref name=\"MikeGikas14\">{{cite news |title=What is Verizon's new high-speed XLTE, and why should I care? |last1=Gikas |first1=Mike |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.consumerreports.org/cro/news/2014/05/what-is-verizon-4g-xlte/index.htm |newspaper=[[Consumer Reports]] |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> The new capacity allowed Verizon to launch what it calls XLTE (LTE on Band 4) in 2013, providing more capacity in congested and well-populated markets.<ref name=\"BrianChen14\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless Names Faster Part of Its Network: XLTE |last1=Chen |first1=Brian X. |last2= |first2= |url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/verizon-wireless-names-faster-part-of-its-network-xlte/?_r=0 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 19, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBecause 4G LTE is a [[data transmission|data-transmitting]] network, when it launched, Verizon customers' voice calls were still carried over the company's [[CDMA2000]] network,<ref name=\"MargueriteReardon14-2\">{{cite news |title=Verizon set to launch voice-over-LTE service nationwide |last1=Reardon |first1=Marguerite |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-readies-launch-of-nationwide-voice-over-lte-service/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=August 26, 2014 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> which was developed for 3G cellphones. In September 2014, Verizon launched [[VoLTE|voice over LTE (VoLTE)]];<ref name=\"PhilGoldstein15\">{{cite news |title=Verizon's Small: We have close to 4M VoLTE customers |last1=Goldstein |first1=Phil |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizons-small-we-have-close-4m-volte-customers/2015-08-11 |newspaper=Fierce Wireless |date=August 11, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> this allowed voice calls to transmit via the data-only LTE network. This also allows for simultaneous voice and data services, something that is unavailable on traditional [[CDMA2000]] calls. Along with VoLTE, Verizon also announced support for [[HDVoice|HD Voice]], which provides higher quality audio for VoLTE calls, and native Video Calling for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones. In March 2016, Verizon enabled support for Wi-Fi Calling, which allows calls to be placed over a Wi-Fi Network. {{as of|2015|August}}, nearly 4 million of Verizon's 103.7 million subscribers used VoLTE.<ref name=\"PhilGoldstein15\" />\n\nA report by [[RootMetrics]] on carrier performance in the first half of 2015 ranked Verizon's network as the best in overall national performance, network reliability, network speed, data performance and call performance.<ref name=MatthewMiller15>{{cite news |title=RootMetrics says Verizon clear leader in wireless performance, T-Mobile CEO furious |last1=Miller |first1=Matthew |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/rootmetrics-report-verizon-the-clear-leader-in-wireless-performance-t-mobiles-john-legere-rants/ |newspaper=[[ZDNet]] |date=August 18, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> For the second half of 2015, RootMetrics's RootScore Report ranked Verizon Wireless No. 1 in overall performance, network speed, network reliability, call performance and data performance.<ref name=RogerCheng16>{{cite news |title=OK, this is the fastest wireless carrier in the nation |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-t-mobile-att-sprint-who-is-the-fastest-carrier-in-the-nation/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=February 17, 2016 |accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> Verizon Wireless and AT&T tied for first in text performance.<ref name=RogerCheng16/>\n\nIn September 2015, Verizon's chief information and technology architect Roger Gurnani stated that Verizon was planning to trial a [[5G]] wireless network within 12 months, with \"some level of commercial deployment\" by 2017.<ref name=RogerCheng15/> In late-August 2016, Verizon officially announced that it had rolled out [[LTE Advanced]] services in 461 markets. The company promoted that the technology would allow at least 50% higher LTE data speeds on supported devices.<ref name=\"verge-ltea\">{{cite web|title=Verizon's faster LTE service is now available in over 450 cities|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/29/12693030/verizon-lte-advanced-461-cities-launched-faster-data-speeds|website=The Verge|date=August 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2019, Verizon had launched 5G service in 30 cities across the U.S.<ref name=\"de Looper19\">{{cite news |title=Verizon reaches goal of 5G in 30 cities in 2019, adds Cleveland and Columbus |last1=de Looper |first1=Christian |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/verizon-5g-rollout/ |work=[[Digital Trends]] |date=December 23, 2019 |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Verizon's 5G network is deployed on [[Extremely_high_frequency|millimeter wave]] spectrum (mmWave).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiercewireless.com/tech/verizon-ceo-defends-mmwave-strategy-for-5g|title=Verizon CEO defends mmWave strategy for 5G|last=Alleven|first=Monica|date=2020-01-30|website=FierceWireless|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> While fast, the high-band spectrum Verizon uses has limited range and high penetration loss.<ref name=\"Sherman20\">{{cite news |title=There are three types of 5G \u2014 most of what you'll get is not the super-fast kind |last1=Sherman |first1=Alex |last2=Haselton |first2=Todd |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/09/what-is-5g-heres-what-verizon-att-sprint-and-t-mobile-offer.html |work=[[CNBC]] |date=January 9, 2020 |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Falahy|first=Naser|last2=Alani|first2=Omar|date=November 2018|title=Millimetre wave frequency band as a candidate spectrum for 5G network architecture: A survey|journal=Physical Communication|language=en|volume=32|pages=120\u2013144|doi=10.1016/j.phycom.2018.11.003}}</ref>\n\n===Radio frequency summary===\n{{further|GSM frequency bands|UMTS frequency bands|LTE frequency bands|NR frequency bands}}\n\nThe following is a list of known 2G, 3G, LTE, and NR frequency bands which Verizon employs in the United States:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Frequency bands used on the Verizon Network\n|-\n! Frequency Band                        !! Band Number !! Protocol !! Generation !! Status !! Notes\n|-\n| '''850'''&nbsp;MHz CLR ||0\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[1xRTT]]/[[EV-DO]]/[[eHRPD]]|| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2G]]/[[3G]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Active/Refarming to 4G LTE<ref name=\"fiercewireless1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/node/162946|title=Verizon to start refarming PCS spectrum for LTE in 2015|last=Marek|first=Sue|date=June 27, 2013|access-date=September 12, 2016|work=FierceWireless}}</ref> || rowspan=\"3\" | Verizon is currently refarming spectrum used for its 2G/3G CDMA networks to 4G LTE in markets where additional LTE capacity is needed; refarming is scheduled be completed by the end of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.commsupdate.com/articles/2019/08/01/verizon-extends-5g-coverage-to-four-more-cities-postpones-3g-shutdown-until-2020/ |title=Verizon extends 5G coverage to four more cities; postpones 3G shutdown until 2020 |website=CommsUpdate |publisher=TeleGeography |date=2019-08-01 |accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''1900'''&nbsp;MHz PCS || 1\n|-\n|'''850'''&nbsp;MHz CLR\n|5|| rowspan=\"4\" | [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] || rowspan=\"4\" | [[4G]]\n|-\n|'''1900'''&nbsp;MHz PCS\n|2\n|Third layer of LTE coverage, used to relieve congestion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phonearena.com/news/Cheat-sheet-which-4G-LTE-bands-do-AT-T-Verizon-T-Mobile-and-Sprint-use-in-the-USA_id77933|title=Cheat sheet: which 4G LTE bands do AT&T, Verizon, T-Mobile and Sprint use in the USA?|last=Hristov|first=Victor|website=Phone Arena|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''700'''&nbsp;MHz Upper C Block || 13 || rowspan=\"2\" | Active ||Main LTE band, completed deployment mid-2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Segan |first=Sascha |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2421046,00.asp |title=Verizon: Nationwide LTE 'Substantially Complete' &#124; News & Opinion |work=PC Magazine |date=June 27, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''1700/2100'''&nbsp;MHz AWS || 4/66 || Branded as \"XLTE\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Alexis|last=Santos|url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/10/15/verizons-lte-aws-rollout-begins/|title=Verizon's LTE boosted in 'major markets' by new frequency, hits 80 Mbps down (update) |work=[[Engadget]] |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> at launch, this second layer of LTE coverage is used to increased bandwidth in major markets.\n|-\n| '''28'''&nbsp;GHz mmWave || n257/n261 ||  rowspan=\"2\" | [[5G NR|NR]] || rowspan=\"2\" | [[5G]] || rowspan=\"2\" | Active/Building Out || rowspan=\"2\" | mmWave band for high-speed LAA using small cells. Went live in May 2019.\n|-\n| '''39'''&nbsp;GHz mmWave || n260 \n|}{{wide image|Verizon Wireless Store, Norwalk, CT 06854, USA - Feb 2013.jpg|800px|A panoramic view within a Verizon Wireless store, [[Norwalk, Connecticut]], circa February 2013.|alt=A panoramic view within a Verizon Wireless Store, Norwalk, CT, United States}}\n\n==RootMetrics RootScore awards==\n\nVerizon has historically done well on [[RootMetrics]] RootScore Reports.<ref name=Baig16>{{cite news |title=Study: Verizon takes top networking honors |last1=Baig |first1=Edward |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/baig/2016/02/18/study-verizon-takes-top-networking-honors/80522048/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=February 18, 2016 |accessdate=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ RootMetrics US national RootScore reports<ref name=RootScore15>{{cite web |url=http://www.rootmetrics.com/en-US/rootscore/map/national/united-states/2015/2H |title=RootScore Awards |author= |date=2016 |publisher=RootMetrics |accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref>\n! Report Date\n! Overall Performance rank\n! Call Performance rank\n! Text Performance rank\n! Data Performance rank\n! Network Speed rank\n! Network Reliability rank\n|-\n! 2nd Half\n2013\n| rowspan=\"13\" | '''1st Place'''\n| rowspan=\"13\" |'''1st Place'''\n| '''1st Place'''\n| rowspan=\"13\" |'''1st Place'''\n| 2nd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n| rowspan=\"13\" | '''1st Place'''\n|-\n! 1st Half\n2014\n| 2nd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n| rowspan=\"12\" |'''1st Place'''\n|-\n! 2nd Half\n2014\n| 3rd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]], #2: [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]])\n|-\n! 1st Half\n2015\n| 2nd Place\n(#1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n|-\n! 2nd Half\n2015\n| '''1st Place'''\n(Tied #1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]])\n|-\n!1st Half\n2016\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''1st Place'''\n|-\n!2nd Half\n2016\n|-\n!1st Half\n2017\n|'''1st Place'''\n(Tied #1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]], [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]])\n|- \n!2nd Half\n2017\n|'''1st Place''' (Tied #1: [[AT&T Mobility|AT&T]], [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]])\n|-\n!1st Half\n2018\n| rowspan=\"4\" |'''1st Place''' (Tied #1: [[AT&T]])\n|-\n!2nd Half\n2018\n|-\n!1st Half\n2019\n|-\n!2nd Half 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rootmetrics.com/en-US/content/us-state-of-the-mobile-union-2h-2019|title=US State of the Mobile Union: carrier performance at national, state, and metro levels 2H 2019|last=Anderson|first=Dave|date=2020-01-28|website=RootMetrics|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n== Apps ==\nVerizon Wireless offers certain applications and services that are exclusive to its subscribers. Many of these [[mobile app|apps]] are pre-loaded on Verizon devices\u2014primarily [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphones. The company has received criticism for this practice, as users and critics have viewed the applications to be [[Pre-installed software|\"bloatware\"]] that are sometimes redundant to applications already included with the device's operating system.<ref name=\"laptop-s5remove\">{{cite web|title=Samsung Galaxy S5 Bloatware Removal Guide|url=http://blog.laptopmag.com/galaxy-s5-bloatware-list|website=Laptop Magazine|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=wired-androidbloatware>{{cite journal|title=Bloatware Creeps Into Android Phones|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/07/bloatware-android-phones/|journal=Wired|date=July 22, 2010}}</ref><ref name=time-sorrierstate>{{cite web|title=Friday Rant: The Ever-Sorrier State of Android Bloatware|url=http://time.com/94646/android-bloatware/|website=Time|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe NFL Mobile app allows Verizon Wireless subscribers to stream [[National Football League]] games and [[NFL Network]] on their devices. While previously a subscription-based service, NFL Mobile was made free to all subscribers beginning in the [[2015 NFL season]]. As part of an exclusivity agreement with the NFL, only Verizon Wireless subscribers could stream NFL telecasts to devices with screens {{convert|7|in|cm}} or less in size. This contract ended after the [[2017 NFL season]];<ref name=exclusive/><ref name=variety12616>{{cite web|title=CBS Tackles New Game With Super Bowl 50: Digital Viewers And Live-Streamed Ads|work=Variety|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=January 28, 2016|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/super-bowl-commercials-cbs-live-streaming-digital-1201688878/}}</ref><ref name=\"cbs-where\">{{cite web|title=Super Bowl 2016: How to watch Super Bowl 50 on TV, online on CBS|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25438861/how-to-watch-super-bowl-50-on-tv-online-and-halftime-show-information|publisher=CBSSports.com|accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SpranglerSeptember42015\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless Drops $5 Monthly Fee to Watch NFL Live Games for All Customers |last1=Spangler |first1=Todd |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/business/20150903_Reuters_MT1VRT1201585307_Verizon_Wireless_Drops__5_Monthly_Fee_to_Watch_NFL_Live_Games_for_All_Customers.html  |agency=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 4, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon agreed to a new five-year, non-exclusive digital rights agreement, which removes the device class exclusivity, and focuses more upon distributing its streams and other enhanced digital content via its [[Oath Inc.|portfolio of internet media brands]], rather than being exclusive to Verizon Wireless subscribers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/21737823/verizon-nfl-agree-new-5-year-deal-worth-nearly-25-billion|title=Verizon, NFL agree to new 5-year deal worth nearly $2.5 billion|first=Darren|last=Rovell|work=ESPN.com|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=exclusive>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2017/10/23/Leagues-and-Governing-Bodies/NFL-notes.aspx|title=Verizon's exclusivity for live games on mobile expected to end|website=Sports Business Daily|language=en-US|date=October 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs part of a deal that also granted the carrier [[title sponsor]]ship of the series, Verizon subscribers also have access to exclusive streaming content within the official [[IndyCar Series]] app.<ref name=\"CardenasMay242015\">{{cite news |title=App brings IndyCar racing from the track to mobile devices |last1=Cardenas |first1=Edward |last2= |first2= |url=http://detroit.cbslocal.com/2015/05/24/app-brings-indycar-racing-from-the-track-to-mobile-devices/ |work=CBSDetroit.com |date=May 24, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe My Verizon app is used for account management, including checking usage statistics and managing the user's service plan and account features.<ref name=\"usatoday-newplans16\">{{cite web|title=Verizon's new plans raise prices for more data|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2016/07/06/amid-growing-competition-verizon-revamps-data-plans/86755334/|website=USA Today|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"KomandoSeptember222014\">{{cite web |url=http://www.komando.com/apps/273517/verizon-app-see-usage-network-performance-set-limits-and-more |title=Verizon App: See usage, network performance, set limits and more |author=Komando staff |date=September 22, 2014 |work=[[Kim Komando|Kommando.com]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813232230/http://www.komando.com/apps/273517/verizon-app-see-usage-network-performance-set-limits-and-more |archive-date=August 13, 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"BereznakOctober242014\">{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/tech/how-to-lock-down-your-data-usage-once-and-for-all-100825489429.html |title=How to lock down your data usage once and for all |first=Alyssa|last=Bereznak |date=October 24, 2014 |work=[[Yahoo!]] Tech |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon Cloud, which allows photos, videos, contacts, messages and call logs to be synchronized online, was released in April 2013 initially for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones,<ref name=\"FingasApril292013\">{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/04/29/verizon-cloud-backup-app-rolling-out-for-android-coming-to-ios/ |title=Verizon Cloud backup service rolling out for Android, comes soon to iOS |first=Jon|last=Fingas |date=April 29, 2013 |work=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> followed the next month by a launch for [[iOS]].<ref name=\"FingasApril292013\"/><ref name=\"WhitneyMay242013\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-cloud-adds-online-storage-for-ios-devices/ |title=Verizon Cloud adds online storage for iOS devices |first=Lance|last=Whitney |date=May 24, 2013 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WhitneyMay242013\"/>  Verizon Messages, otherwise known as Message+, is an alternative [[text messaging]] app that additionally allows messages to be synchronized between multiple devices.<ref name=\"MusilMarch212013\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/new-verizon-app-untethers-text-messages-from-your-cell-phone/ |title=New Verizon app untethers text messages from your cell phone |first=Steven|last=Musil |date=March 21, 2013 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> VZ Navigator is a subscription-based [[map]]s and [[navigation]] service which provides [[turn-by-turn navigation]], [[crowdsourcing|crowdsourced]] [[traffic]] [[data]], weather, events and entertainment listings, gas prices, roadside assistance, 2D and 3D views.<ref name=\"LendinoMarch232010\">{{cite news |title=VZ Navigator 5 review |last1=Lendino |first1=Jamie |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2361689,00.asp |magazine=[[PC Magazine]] |date=March 23, 2010 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> The Verizon Support & Protection app provides technical support services, lost device location, and on Android, antivirus functionality.<ref name=\"ChuangFebruary232015\">{{cite news |title=Mailbag: Most Internet providers offer antivirus software for free |last1=Chuang |first1=Tamara |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.denverpost.com/techmailbag/ci_27569296/mailbag-most-internet-providers-offer-antivirus-software-free |newspaper=[[The Denver Post]] |date=February 23, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVerizon Family Locator is a subscription-based service and app can be used to track the locations of family members on a map for up to 10 devices.<ref name=\"RosenbloomJune132013\">{{cite news |title=Where is everyone? Try a tracking app |last1=Rosenbloom |first1=Stephanie |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/16/travel/where-is-everyone-try-a-tracking-app.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 13, 2013 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=WebsterJune242013>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/six-ways-to-share-your-exact-location-with-family-and-why/ |title=Six ways to share your exact location with family (and why) |first=Scott|last=Webster |date=June 24, 2013 |publisher=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon Family Base allows parents to restrict when and how their children use their phones, view their children's contacts and lock the devices.<ref name=\"WebsterJune242013\"/><ref name=\"ChengFebruary132014\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/so-is-verizons-more-everything-plan-a-good-deal/ |title=So is Verizon's 'More Everything' plan a good deal? |first=Roger|last=Cheng |date=February 13, 2014 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Verizon also offers the GizmoPal, a wristband-worn phone for children that is restricted to only placing or receiving calls from one of two designated caregivers, and has [[GPS tracking unit|GPS tracking]].<ref name=\"AlvarezNovember262014\">{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/11/26/lg-gizmopal-verizon/ |title=LG GizmoPal wearable lets kids call their parents with one button |first=Edgar|last=Alvarez |date=November 26, 2014 |work=[[Engadget]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"SeganJanuary302015\">{{cite news |title=LG GizmoPal (Verizon Wireless) |last1=Segan |first1=Sascha |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2475924,00.asp |newspaper=[[PC Magazine]] |date=January 30, 2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther Verizon Wireless apps include Field Force Manager, which allows employers to manage employees with GPS, management timesheets and oversee travel,<ref name=\"BreedenJune52014\">{{cite web |url=http://gcn.com/articles/2014/06/05/cheektowaga-xora.aspx |title=GPS, geofencing drive highway department efficiency |author=John Breeden II |date=June 5, 2014 |publisher=GCN |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Visual Voice Mail<ref name=\"BradleyDecember312014\">{{cite news |title=Crucial features iPhone users just take for granted |last1=Bradley |first1=Tony |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tonybradley/2014/12/31/crucial-features-iphone-users-just-take-for-granted/ |newspaper=[[Forbes]] |date=December 31, 2014 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> and Roadside Assistance.<ref name=\"HarrisDemandMedia\">{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless and Roadside Assistance |last1=Harris |first1=Brad |last2= |first2= |url=http://smallbusiness.chron.com/verizon-wireless-roadside-assistance-27324.html  |agency=[[Demand Media]] |date= |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ColleyJuly202012\">{{cite news |title=5 ways to get cheap (or even free) roadside assistance |last1=Colley |first1=Angela |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/Saving-Money/2012/0720/5-ways-to-get-cheap-or-even-free-roadside-assistance |newspaper=[[Christian Science Monitor]] |date=July 20, 2012 |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Products and services==\nVerizon Wireless offers mobile phone, home telephone, and Internet services through a variety of devices.\n\n===Wireless phone services===\nVerizon Wireless offers smartphones powered by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iOS]], [[Google]]'s [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Microsoft]]'s [[Windows Phone]] and [[BlackBerry OS]].<ref name=ReutersProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/companyProfile?symbol=VZ.N |title=Profile: Verizon Communications Inc. |author= |date= |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate= February 4, 2016}}</ref> Both its [[Feature phone|basic phones]] and smartphones use their 4G LTE network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashgear.com/verizon-launches-its-first-4g-lte-basic-phone-16488613/|title=Verizon launches its first 4G LTE basic phone|date=2017-06-16|website=SlashGear|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> The company offers different voice and data plans for its users.<ref name=ChloeAlbanesius>{{cite news |title=New Verizon plans ditch phone subsidies, contracts |last1=Albanesius |first1=Chloe |last2= |first2= |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2489253,00.asp |newspaper=[[PC Magazine]] |date=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=RogerCheng>{{cite news |title=Verizon kills off service contracts, smartphone subsidies |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-kills-off-service-contracts-smartphone-subsidies/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Wireless home phone===\nIntroduced in February 2015 as Verizon Wireless Home Phone Connect, Wireless Home Phone uses Verizon's cellular network rather than using traditional landline wires to provide home phone service.<ref name=RyanKnutson>{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless gets a boost from home phones \u2014 yes, home phones |last1=Knutson |first1=Ryan |last2= |first2= |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/corporate-intelligence/2014/04/24/verizon-wireless-gets-a-boost-from-home-phones-yes-home-phones/ |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=April 24, 2014 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Mobile Wi-Fi and broadband===\nVerizon Wireless sells Wi-Fi hotspot devices, branded as Jetpack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/support/verizon-jetpack-faqs/|title=Verizon Jetpack FAQs - Mobile Hotspot|website=www.verizonwireless.com|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The company offered home Internet service through a 4G LTE Broadband Router with Voice that can connect up to 10 devices over Wi-Fi as well as home phone service.<ref name=RogerCheng092513>{{cite news |title=Verizon Wireless nudges into home phone, broadband biz |last1=Cheng |first1=Roger |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/verizon-wireless-nudges-into-home-phone-broadband-biz/ |newspaper=[[CNET]] |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref> This service and device have since been discontinued.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verizonwireless.com/home-office-solutions/verizon-lte-internet-and-home-phone/|title=Verizon LTE Internet and Home Phone|website=Verizon Wireless|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==LTE in Rural America<span id=\"LRA\"></span>==\nThe LTE in Rural America Program (or LRA program), introduced in May 2010, covers 2.7 million potential users over {{convert|225000|mi2|km2|}} in 169 rural counties.<ref name=PhilGoldstein15-2>{{cite news |title=Verizon: All 21 LTE in Rural America carrier partners have launched service |last1=Goldstein |first1=Phil |last2= |first2= |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/verizon-all-21-lte-rural-america-carrier-partners-have-launched-service/2015-10-15 |newspaper=Fierce Wireless |date=October 15, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> Under this program, partners lease spectrum from Verizon Wireless and connect to the company's network, and Verizon provides technical support and resources to help the rural wireless company build out its own 4G LTE network. The program extends the footprint of 4G LTE coverage for both the rural carrier and Verizon, as customers can take advantage of both networks.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Verizon's LTE in Rural America (LRA) Program Celebrates Five Years of Delivering Advanced Wireless Services to Rural Customers|url = http://www.verizonwireless.com/news/article/2015/05/verizons-lte-in-rural-america-lra-program-celebrates-five-years-of-delivering-advanced-wireless-services-to-rural-customers.html|website = Verizon Wireless News Center|accessdate = May 20, 2015}}</ref> {{as of|2015}}, all LRA members have fully rolled out their 4G LTE networks. \n\nCarriers who participated in the program are:\n\n* Appalachian Wireless\n* Bluegrass Cellular\n* Carolina West Wireless\n* [[Cellcom (United States)|Cellcom]]\n* Chariton Valley\n* Chat Mobility\n* Copper Valley Telecom\n* Bravado Wireless (former Sprocket Wireless by Cross Telephone)\n* Custer Telephone Cooperative\n* Ketchikan Public Utilities\n* Nemont\n* NorthwestCell\n* Pioneer Cellular\n* STRATA Networks\n* Southwestern Wireless (formerly Key Communications)\n* S & R Communications\n* Thumb Cellular\n* Triangle Mobile\n* Wireless Partners\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of mobile phone standards]]\n* [[GreatCall]]\n* [[Librestream]]\n* [[Page Plus Cellular]]\n* [[Venturi Transport Protocol]]\n* [[Vodafone#The Americas|Vodafone in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.verizonwireless.com Official website]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000519214314/http://www.verizonwireless.com/ |date=May 19, 2000 |title=Verizon Wireless }}\n\n{{Verizon Wireless}}\n{{Verizon}}\n{{US mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Verizon Wireless| ]]\n[[Category:Verizon Communications|Wireless]]\n[[Category:Vodafone]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Somerset County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Bernards Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Multinational joint-venture companies]]\n", "name_user": "CookieMonster755", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verizon_Wireless"}
{"title_page": "Jamie Paterson (footballer, born 1991)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Jamie Paterson\n| image       = Jamie Paterson.jpg\n| image_size  = 200\n| caption     = Paterson with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in 2016\n| fullname    = Jamie Charles Stuart Paterson<ref name=\"Professional retain list & free transfers 2012/13\">{{Cite news\n |title=Professional retain list & free transfers 2012/13 \n |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0,,10794~179534,00.pdf \n |publisher=The Football League \n |format=PDF \n |date=18 May 2013 \n |page=49 \n |accessdate=2 July 2013 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802074454/http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0%2C%2C10794~179534%2C00.pdf \n |archivedate= 2 August 2014 \n}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1991|12|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Coventry]], England\n| height      = {{height|ft=5|in=11}}\n| position    = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]], [[Forward (football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| clubnumber  = 20\n| years1 = 2010\u20132013 | clubs1 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]]                                | caps1 = 94 | goals1 = 15\n| years2 = 2013\u20132016 | clubs2 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]            | caps2 = 55 | goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] (loan) | caps3 = 34 | goals3 = 6\n| years4 = 2016\u2013     | clubs4 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]                      | caps4 = 110 | goals4 = 17\n| years5 = 2019\u20132020 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Derby County F.C|Derby County]] (loan)              | caps5 = 10 | goals5 = 1\n| club-update = 23:46, 10 February 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Jamie Charles Jenson Ravenscroft Stuart Paterson''' (born 20 December 1991), is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].   He can operate as both a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] and [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref>Post, Nottingham. (5 August 2014) [http://www.nottinghampost.com/Jamie-Paterson-looks-prove-new-boss-Pearce/story-22073678-detail/story.html Jamie Paterson looks to prove himself to new boss Pearce at Nottingham Forest] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140807011825/http://www.nottinghampost.com/Jamie-Paterson-looks-prove-new-boss-Pearce/story-22073678-detail/story.html |date=7 August 2014 }}. Nottingham Post. Retrieved on 18 February 2016.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Walsall===\nBorn in [[Coventry]], Paterson made his senior d\u00e9but for [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] on 31 August 2010, in a 2\u20131 defeat to [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] in the [[Football League Trophy]],<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8951124.stm \"Walsall 1\u20132 Chesterfield\"] BBC Sport. 31 August 2010. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> making his league d\u00e9but four days later, in a 1\u20130 home loss to [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/8964111.stm \"Walsall 0\u20131 Colchester\"] BBC Sport. 4 September 2010. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> His first goal for the club came over a year later, as he scored in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] on 5 November 2011.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15504320 \"Huddersfield 1\u20131 Walsall\"] BBC Sport. 5 November 2011. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> His second and third league goals came in a 2\u20131 loss to [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] on 2 January 2012,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16331439 \"Bury 2\u20131 Walsall\"] BBC Sport. 2 January 2012. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> and in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 20 March.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17349082 \"Sheffield Wed 2\u20132 Walsall\"] BBC Sport. 20 March 2012. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> His first goal of the 2012\u201313 season came on 1 September, as he opened the scoring in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19378090 \"Walsall 2\u20132 Brentford\"] BBC Sport. 1 September 2012. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> His scoring rate increased from his previous two seasons, and he scored his seventh goal of the season on 1 January 2013 to give Walsall a 1\u20130 win against [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20840902 \"Walsall 1\u20130 Stevenage\"] BBC Sport. 1 January 2013. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> He then stated that his target for the season was to score 10 goals, and that the team had regained their confidence following three wins in the last four games.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20888003 \"Walsall: Jamie Paterson says Saddlers have belief back\"] BBC Sport. 2 January 2013. Retrieved 4 January 2013.</ref> On 2 February, he scored twice in a 3\u20131 win against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21209389 \"Walsall 3\u20131 Oldham\"] BBC Sport. 2 February 2013. Retrieved 2 February 2013.</ref> On 1 April, he gave a superb performance against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] by scoring twice in a 4\u20130 win<ref>{{cite news|title=Walsall 4\u20130 Coventry|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21921213|date=1 April 2013|accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Nottingham Forest===\nOn 2 July 2013, Paterson signed for [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on a three-year deal. The fee was undisclosed, however it was believed it was a six-figure fee with add-ons taking the total amount beyond \u00a31million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Walsall's Jamie Paterson sold to Nottingham Forest|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/other-football/walsall-fc/2013/07/02/walsall-sell-jamie-paterson-to-nottingham-forest/|accessdate=2 July 2013}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a pre-season friendly against Belgian side [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] on 20 July.<ref>[http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/forest-royal-antwerp-200713-927648.aspx \"Forest 2\u20132 Royal Antwerp\"] Nottingham Forest. 20 July 2013. Retrieved 27 July 2013.</ref> His first competitive goals came when he scored a hat-trick against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in the [[2013-14 FA Cup|FA Cup]] third round on 5 January 2014.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25539803 \"Nottingham Forest 5\u20130 West Ham United\"] BBC Sport. 5 January 2014. Retrieved 21 January 2014.</ref> He scored his first league goal for the club in the following game, opening the scoring in a 1\u20131 draw away at [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25599436 \"Bolton Wanderers 1\u20131 Nottingham Forest\"] BBC Sport. 11 January 2014. Retrieved 21 January 2014.</ref> He scored for the third game in a row on 18 January, scoring in a 4\u20131 win at home to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25692316\"Nottingham Forest 4\u20131 Blackburn Rovers] BBC Sport. 18 January 2014. Retrieved 21 January 2014.</ref> On 11 February, he scored twice in a 3\u20130 win against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26027861 \"Huddersfield Town 0\u20133 Nottm Forest\"] BBC Sport. 11 February 2014. Retrieved 11 February 2014.</ref> Paterson finished the 2013\u201314 season scoring 12 goals in 39 appearances in all competitions.\n\nWith the signing of [[Michail Antonio]] in the close season, Paterson's game time was not as frequent during the 2014\u201315 season. He made 25 appearances in all competitions, scoring only once in a 5\u20133 victory against Fulham on 17 September 2014.\n\n====Huddersfield Town loan====\nOn 1 September 2015, as the transfer window closed, Paterson joined [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] on a season-long loan with a view to making the move permanent.<ref>[http://www.htafc.com/news/article/huddersfield-town-jamie-paterson-nottingham-forest-2663194.aspx Jamie Paterson joins Huddersfield Town on loan from Nottingham Forest]. Htafc.com. Retrieved on 18 February 2016.</ref> He made his d\u00e9but for Town in the 2\u20130 loss against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] on 12 September. He scored his first goal for the club in the 2\u20130 win over [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] on 21 October 2015.\n\n===Bristol City===\nOn 27 August 2016, Paterson was presented to Bristol City fans as a new signing, on a three-year contract.<ref>BBC Radio Bristol.</ref> He scored his first goal for Bristol City in a 2\u20131 win against former club Nottingham Forest on 1 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37458625\n|title=Bristol City 2\u20131 Nottingham Forest\n|publisher=BBC\n|date=1 October 2016\n|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> Paterson featured as Bristol City reached  the semi finals of the [[2017-18 EFL Cup]] with wins over [[Premier League]] opponents [[Watford FC]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40932205|title=Watford 2-3 Bristol City|date=22 August 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Stoke City]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41235275|title=Bristol City 2-0 Stoke City|date=19 September 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Crystal Palace F.C.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41647095|title=Bristol City 4-1 Crystal Palace|date=24 October 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and [[Manchester United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42334221|title=Bristol City 2-1 Manchester United|date=20 December 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Paterson played as City lost in the semi-final tie against [[Premier League]] leaders [[Manchester City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42537815|title=Manchester City 2-1 Bristol City|date=9 January 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 January 2019 Paterson featured as Bristol City won 1-0 to upset [[Premier League]] side [[Huddersfield Town FC]] in the [[FA Cup]] third round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46707012|title=Bristol City 1-0 Huddersfield in FA Cup third round|date=5 January 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n====Derby County loan====\nOn 8 August 2019, as the transfer window closed, Paterson joined [[Derby County F.C|Derby County]] on a season-long loan.<ref>[https://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/2019/08/paterson-joins-derby-to-add-to-attacking-options Jamie Paterson joins Derby County on loan from Bristol City]. dcfc.co.uk. Retrieved on 8 August 2019.</ref> The loan was cut short on 30 December 2019 after Bristol City exercised a recall clause in the loan agreement.<ref>[https://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/2019/12/paterson-to-return-to-bristol-city Paterson To Return To Bristol City]. dcfc.co.uk. Retrieved on 30 December 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/paterson-back-in-bs3/ Paterson Back In BS3]. bcfc.co.uk. Retrieved on 30 December 2019.</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAlthough born in England, Paterson has declared he would be open to play for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], for whom he qualifies through his parents.<ref>Advertiser, Walsall. (19 February 2014) [http://www.walsalladvertiser.co.uk/Scotland-cap-Nottingham-Forest-ace-soon-possible/story-20659198-detail/story.html Walsall boss says ex-Saddlers winger Jamie Paterson is ready for international spotlight] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706084453/http://www.walsalladvertiser.co.uk/Scotland-cap-Nottingham-Forest-ace-soon-possible/story-20659198-detail/story.html |date=6 July 2015 }}. Walsall Advertiser. Retrieved on 18 February 2016.</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 February 2020}}\n\n{| clas